WEBVTT

00:00:00.390 --> 00:00:04.660
There are several ways to display series: either individually or

00:00:04.660 --> 00:00:05.570
grouped together.

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:08.210
Let’s go through this!

00:00:09.540 --> 00:00:13.830
Select the delta O18 and delta C13 series that we

00:00:13.830 --> 00:00:15.110
have just interpolated.

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:18.050
Then choose Display Together.

00:00:19.450 --> 00:00:23.610
Next, select Separated axis: Vertical.

00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:26.660
Invert the axis for the delta O18 series.

00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:32.400
From a scientific perspective, we typically observe reduced benthic delta

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:37.120
C13 values during glacial periods, which correspond to increased benthic

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:40.980
delta O18 values — for example, between 60 and 70

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:41.960
thousands years.

00:00:43.070 --> 00:00:46.830
Now, let’s display the other variables in a stacked view

00:00:48.430 --> 00:00:51.740
From the menu, select Display Stacked.

00:00:52.940 --> 00:00:58.200
From a scientific perspective, we typically observe opposite variations between

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:03.800
calcium proportions—mostly of marine biogenic origin — and other elements

00:01:03.800 --> 00:01:06.180
of continental, terrigenous provenance.

00:01:07.880 --> 00:01:10.520
You may have noticed that the series are linked, because

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:13.490
they share the same name for their horizontal axis.

00:01:14.690 --> 00:01:17.510
However, you can control this behavior.

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:22.010
For example, you can assign the axis of Plot 2

00:01:22.010 --> 00:01:25.990
to a new group, making it independent, while preserving the

00:01:25.990 --> 00:01:28.470
link between Plots 1 and 3.

00:01:31.730 --> 00:01:35.210
By the way, the colors automatically assigned to the series

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:37.820
can be modified using the color picker.
